# Commit identity and sign-off

Every commit in this repo MUST be authored by **GriffinAD** with the paired
email `nigel.surridge@btinternet.com`. This is the user's GitHub identity and
their personal email — **not** the global git identity on this machine, which
belongs to an unrelated work account.

## Before every commit — verify

Run these exact checks before invoking `git commit`:

```bash
test "$(git -C <repo-root> config --local user.name)"  = "GriffinAD"
test "$(git -C <repo-root> config --local user.email)" = "nigel.surridge@btinternet.com"
```

If either check fails, **stop**. Do not commit. Do not silently fix by
updating the global config. Report the mismatch to the human and ask.

## Required sign-off (DCO, ADR-0025)

Every commit MUST include a `Signed-off-by:` trailer matching the identity
above. Use `-s` / `--signoff`:

```bash
git commit -s -m "<subject>"
```

The trailer looks exactly like:

```
Signed-off-by: GriffinAD <nigel.surridge@btinternet.com>
```

A commit without the trailer is a policy violation. Do not amend someone
else's commits to add a trailer without asking.

## No `Made-with: Cursor` trailer (unless the human opts in)

Do **not** add a `Made-with: Cursor` line to commit messages. The
`Signed-off-by:` trailer should be the **final** line of the message.

If the Cursor IDE injects that line, strip it when amending, e.g.:

```bash
git -c core.hooksPath=/dev/null commit --amend -F /path/to/clean-message.txt
```

**Repo hook (recommended):** after clone, run once:

```bash
git config core.hooksPath .githooks
```

The versioned `.githooks/commit-msg` hook removes a trailing `Made-with: Cursor`
line so `Signed-off-by:` stays last.

## Do not touch the global config

- `git config --global user.name` / `user.email` stay untouched.
- The identity override is **repo-local only** (`git config --local ...`).
- If an agent ever needs to re-set the local override (fresh clone, etc.),
  it must ask the human first.

## Message conventions (preferred; not enforced as blocking in current CI)

- Conventional commit subjects: `feat:`, `fix:`, `docs:`, `chore:`,
  `refactor:`, `test:`, `ci:`.
- Subject ≤ 72 chars.
- Body wraps at 72 cols.
- `Signed-off-by:` trailer is the last line of the message (no `Made-with:` after it).

## Phase delivery workflow

For multi-step implementation phases, agents work in **ordered commits** on one
phase branch (for example, `phase5`). Same verification before each commit:

- `bash scripts/check_app.sh`
- `npm run check:docs-text`
- `uv run python scripts/check_release_artifacts.py`

Commit each chunk with sign-off (`git commit -s`). Merge to `main` only when
phase acceptance criteria are met.

If a chunk is materially contentious (architecture/policy uncertainty or
high-risk behavior), pause and ask the human before proceeding.

### Stacked slices (multiple PRs in one phase)

When a phase ships as **several slices** (e.g. observability → scheduler →
discovery), treat them as **one linear branch**, not a braid of merges.

**Do**

- Put slices in **history order** on the same branch: first commit = first
  slice, second = second slice, and so on (plus a final docs/ADR commit if
  needed).
- **Rebase** onto `main` to update the branch:  
  `git fetch origin && git rebase origin/main`  
  Resolve conflicts once; keep the branch **linear** (no merge commits from
  `main` into the phase branch for routine updates).
- Fold small follow-ups for an earlier slice into that slice with  
  `git commit --fixup` + `git rebase -i --autosquash` **before** pushing, when
  it keeps the story one-commit-per-slice.

**Do not**

- `git merge main` (or merge any integration branch) into the phase branch
  repeatedly — that produces merge commits between slices and a hard-to-read
  graph.
- Merge sibling branches into each other to “stack” work — rebase the child
  work onto the parent branch tip instead.
- Rewrite published history (force-push) **without** explicit human approval —
  default is one clean branch pushed once, or coordinated force-with-lease.

If history is already messy, **stop** and ask the human before large cherry-pick
or filter-branch recovery; prefer a documented one-time fix over repeated
history surgery.
